                    <msContents>
                        <summary>An unidentified scribe completed this Qur'ān manuscript (<hi
                                rend="italic">muṣḥāf</hi>) in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                from="1806-11-12" to="1806-12-10">Ramaḍān 1221 AH (12 Nov.–10 Dec.
                                1806 CE)</date>, possibly in <placeName cert="medium"
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1003770" key="place_1003770"
                                >Kurdistan, then in the Ottoman Empire</placeName>.</summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="manuscript_19948-item1">
                            <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">al-Qurʾān</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ara">القران</title>
                            <incipit/>
                            <explicit/>
                            <colophon>The colophon unusually appears on <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                                    >1a</locus></colophon>
                            <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support>Text of <material>paper</material>, handmade in <placeName
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1000003"
                                        key="place_1000003">Europe</placeName>, with ~22 laid lines
                                    per 20 cm and ~24 mm between chain lines, with partial
                                    watermarks evident in the gutters, subsequently externally
                                    tinted medium sienna-brown, and externally sized and polished.
                                    Folios <locus>11–12</locus> replaced and <locus>148–152</locus>
                                    repaired with comparatively thin-weight, eggshell-tinted wove
                                    paper.</support>
                                <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="190">190 folios, 2 flyleaves
                                        (ff. i + 190 + i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf"
                                        unit="mm">
                                        <height>152</height>
                                        <width>103</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height>117</height>
                                        <width>72</width>
                                    </dimensions></extent>
                                <foliation xml:id="modern">Modern pencilled Arabic numerals on the
                                    upper-left corners of the a sides throughout.</foliation>
                                <collation> Primarily a combination of triternions and quaternions
                                    throughout. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the
                                        lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>


                                <condition>Handle text with caution. In poor condition, with stains,
                                    tears, and historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" writtenLines="7 17">1 column with seventeen
                                    lines per page. Replaced folios <locus from="11a" to="12b"
                                        >11–12</locus> with 7–13 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi
                                        rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="naskh" medium="inkBlack">Minute clear
                                black naskh script hand, with chapter headings, verse markers, and
                                khums and ‘ashr divisions indicating every fifth and tenth line
                                respectively in red. </handNote>
                            <handNote scope="minor">Replaced folios <locus from="11a" to="12b"
                                    >11–12</locus> and restored text on <locus from="148a" to="152b"
                                    >148–152</locus> in a comparatively large naskh, Ottoman-style
                                hand.</handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote>Verse divisions marked by small red circles.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <additions><lb/>
                            <label>Marginalia:</label> Various prayers in another hand inscribed at
                            the beginning and end, and occasionally elsewhere in the margins.<lb/>
                            <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="Inner_front_cover"
                                to="Inner_front_cover">right pastedown</locus>:<lb/>
                            <q>Presented to the Free Library<lb/> Wigan<lb/> Crawford, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000874"
                                    key="place_7000874">Rome</placeName>.</q><lb/>
                            <label>Bookplate:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                                to="Inner_back_cover">leftt pastedown</locus>: <lb/>
                            <q>Presented to the Wigan Free Public Library<lb/> The Right Honourable
                                Earl of Crawford and Balcarres, <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1894-08">August, 1894</date>.</q>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1806" notAfter="1825">
                                <p>Probably close to contemporary, <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                        notBefore="1800" notAfter="1825">early 19th century</date>
                                    binding, possibly Ottoman.</p>
                                <p>Abbreviated resewing on three recessed cords. Thin-weight wove
                                    endpapers added to the beginning and end, countermarked
                                            <q><watermark>GB</watermark></q>.<lb/>
                                    <dimensions type="countermark" unit="mm">
                                        <height>25</height>
                                        <width>58</width>
                                    </dimensions>.<lb/> Edges trimmed and cloth endbands adhered to
                                    the head and tail, the former now lost. Boards covered in full,
                                    artificially embossed, claret-coloured, straight-grained
                                    'Morocco' sheepskin <material>leather</material>, hollow-backed,
                                    with squares along the edges and defined joints, but without a
                                    flap (Type III binding per Déroche).</p>
                                <decoNote><locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> panels
                                    divided by foliate decorative pallete, with inverse Gothic
                                    arches at tail.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>157</height>
                                        <width>110</width>
                                        <depth>25</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In poor condition with the
                                    upper headcap broken off, right board hinged with gelatin tape,
                                    and extensive abrasion on the board exteriors.</condition>

                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <sealDesc>
                            <seal type="embossed" subtype="oval">
                                <p>A blind-embossed seal of the <orgName role="rpo"
                                        key="person_315691108" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/315691108"
                                        >Wigan Free Public Library</orgName> appears on the
                                    endpapers, accessory content, and first and last folios:<lb/>
                                    <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                        <height>33</height>
                                        <width>25</width>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                            </seal>
                        </sealDesc>
                        <accMat>A letter adhered on the <locus from="Inner_front_cover"
                                to="Inner_front_cover">right board interior</locus>:<lb/></accMat>

                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>Possibly completed in a province of the <origPlace cert="medium"
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1003770" key="place_1003770"
                                >Kurdistan, then in the Ottoman Empire</origPlace>
                            <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1806-11-12" to="1806-12-10"
                                >Ramaḍān 1221 AH (12 Nov.–10 Dec. 1806 CE)</origDate>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in
                                    <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7008653"
                                    cert="high">Britain</placeName> remain unclear, <persName
                                    type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                                    key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                                    and 8th Earl of Balcarres (1812–1880)</persName> possibly acquired it
                                from an unidentified source for his <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552"
                                    >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Probably inherited by <persName role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James
                                    Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>, who then presented it as a
                                gift to the <orgName role="rpo"
                                    key="person_315691108" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/315691108"
                                    >Wigan Free Public Library</orgName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1894-08">August, 1894</date>. </p></provenance>
                        <acquisition><p>Transferred to the <orgName role="rpo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/7632154387289530970002"
                                    key="person_7632154387289530970002">Archives: Wigan &amp;
                                    Leigh</orgName> <!-- in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="2023"
                                    >2023</date> -->.</p></acquisition>
                    </history>
